g.title: Folded Corner.205
g.desc: The Interpreter pattern compliments the Single Responsibility...

g.text: The Interpreter pattern compliments the Single Responsibility Principle. The Interpreter pattern expresses a class for each Grammar rule. A Grammar rule is called an Expression. An Expression can be relatively simple, for example adding up two integers. The Parser (=client) can compose these expressions in an AST structure. After parsing, interpretation of the AST takes place. The result of this interpretation is a different representation or action. The client (=Parser) and Grammar are separated from each other. This results in reusability, testability, stability and flexibility and maintainability. Reusability, because different Parsers can re-use the same Grammar and new Grammar rules can inherit from existing ones. Testability, because each grammar rule can be tested in isolation because it is not directly expressed within the Parser. Stability, because the impact of changing a grammar rule represented by a single class is minimized in contrast to expressing the grammar directly in the Parser. Flexibility, because an expression can be queued for interpretation. (E.g. waiting until another expression is interpreted). Maintainability, each grammar rule defines its own class, enabling ‘shrinkage’ of the problem window. This enables identifying problems faster. If the problem is related to the composition of the AST, the problem lies in the Parser. If the problem is related to interpretation, the problem lies in the grammar.

g.title: Folded Corner.216
g.desc: The Interpreter pattern is most appropriate in case the langu...

g.text: The Interpreter pattern is most appropriate in case the language does not define an extensive Grammar. Using the Interpreter pattern for extensive Grammars can become complex and unmanageable, because we need to define each Grammar rule and construct ASTs from it. In case of an extensive Grammar it might be more appropriate to switch to a Parser generator. A Parser generator can be seen as a ‘Parser Parser’. The Grammar can be specified via a more abstract language and will be interpreted by a parser into another Parser. The generated Parser can construct a parse tree based on our Grammar definition. This parse tree can be interpreted and generate a different representation.

g.title: Folded Corner.196
g.desc: The Interpreter violates the Single Responsibility Principle....

g.text: The Interpreter violates the Single Responsibility Principle. The growth in size and complexity of a Grammar can ensure a class ‘explosion’. This is caused by specifying each Grammar rule as a separate class. This results in a scattered code base that becomes hard to maintain and navigate through. Parser generators can be used as a resolution for extensive grammars.

g.title: Folded Corner.235
g.desc: The purpose of the Interpreter pattern is to evaluate sentenc...

g.text: The purpose of the Interpreter pattern is to evaluate sentences in a language and interpreting it into another more sophisticated one. The pattern distinguishes between terminal and non-terminal symbols. Terminal symbols are the symbols that form the base of a language. A terminal symbol is a also called a ‘Leave’. Non-terminal symbols merge Terminal and Non-Terminal symbols. A Non-Terminal symbol is a Composite. E.g. in the mathematical expression: 1+2. ‘1’ and ‘2’ are terminal. The ‘+’ is Non-Terminal. A Grammar is defined by Non-Terminal and Terminal Symbols (=Lexical elements). The Interpreter pattern specifies an object for each Terminal and Non-Terminal symbol. An Abstract Syntax Tree (=AST) can be composed from these Lexical elements. The Interpreter is used to evaluate/Interpret the AST based on a given Context. The Interpreter pattern doesn’t express how to parse the Lexical input into an AST.

g.title: Folded Corner.247
g.desc: The Interpreter pattern compliments the Open Closed Principle...

g.text: The Interpreter pattern compliments the Open Closed Principle. The Open Closed principle is supported by the Dependency Inversion Principle. Each Expression in the Interpreter pattern implements and/or is dependent on an abstraction. The abstraction enables reusability and stability. Reusability, because different concrete expressions (Terminal or Non Terminal) can be injected in the Non Terminal Expression. (Non) Terminal Expressions are not dependent on details, but on an abstractions. Non Terminal Expressions are reusable across multiple Expressions. Stability, because the Non Terminal Expression is dependent on an abstraction. It can change its behavior without direct modification. Multiple different Expression can be injected in the Non Terminal Expression and it will ‘behave’ differently. This enables code stability, because we can introduce new Expressions and inject it into existing expressions without modifying the existing expressions.

g.title: Folded Corner.251
g.desc: The Interpreter pattern expresses parse trees often in the fo...

g.text: The Interpreter pattern expresses parse trees often in the form of an Abstract Syntax Tree. However, a parse tree can also be expressed in a Finite State Automata (=FSA). E.g.: an Asterisk symbol (*) in a Regular expression Matcher can be expressed as a self-transition of a Literal Expression. The FSA in a Regular Expression Matcher can be a Deterministic Finite Automata (DFA) or a Deterministic Finite Automata (NFA). A DFA contains a unique state transition path for a given Regular Expression and input string. This results in more defined states. A NFA contains alternative transition paths for a given Regular Expression and input string. This results in less defined states. The DFA is linear time, but consumes more space. The NFA could lead to exponential time, but consumes less space.
